{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"12989a56-d846-41c1-8f85-cac9c858d6e6","content":"**The problem: \"Scoped\" means something different in MAUI.**\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, a scoped service lives for one HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no request pipeline — the default scope is the **entire app lifetime**. So `AddScoped` behaves essentially like `AddSingleton`, and your DbContext's change tracker accumulates state across navigations.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient<MyDbContext>()`** — gives a fresh instance each time it's injected.\n\n2. **Create scopes manually** via `IServiceScopeFactory`:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Clear tracking** when navigating:\n   ```csharp\n   dbContext.ChangeTracker.Clear();\n   ```\n\nOption 1 is the simplest if your pages don't share a unit-of-work. Option 2 gives you explicit control over the DbContext lifetime per \"logical operation.\"","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"91515af7-503e-4614-a89d-4d1bb3d108e0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, \"scoped\" means per-HTTP-request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request, so \"scoped\" effectively behaves like a singleton — the scope never ends during the app's lifetime. That's why the DbContext persists across page navigations.","outputTokens":392,"requestId":"942B:EB431:1452949:16CDB54:6A06736C"},"id":"608d4e7d-25e1-42d1-9a30-49d311bab9c3","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:14:30.140Z","parentId":"583011f2-0522-4dcd-a87c-5a67a0365cac"}
